# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adirondack-mountains
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] The **1932 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **III Olympic Winter Games** and commonly known as **Lake Placid 1932**, were a winter multi-sport event in the United States, held in Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] The games opened on February 4 and closed on February 13.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] It was the first time the Winter Games were held outside of Europe and the first of four Winter Olympics held in the United States; Lake Placid hosted again in 1980.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] The games were awarded to Lake Placid in part by the efforts of Godfrey Dewey, head of the Lake Placid Club and son of Melvil Dewey, inventor of the Dewey Decimal System.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] California also had a bid for the 1932 Winter Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] William May Garland, president of the California X Olympiad Association, wanted the games to take place in Wrightwood and Big Pines, California.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] The world's largest ski jump at the time was constructed in Big Pines for the event, but the games were ultimately awarded to Lake Placid.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] The practice of awarding Olympic medals at podium ceremonies was established at the 1932 Winter Olympics, based on pedestals used at the 1930 British Empire Games, as proposed by Melville Marks Robinson.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 14 events contested in 4 sports (7 disciplines).
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] The Games also included events in three demonstration sports.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] Athletes from 17 nations competed in these Games, down from 25 nations at the previous Games in 1928.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1932-winter-olympics] Argentina, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Mexico, the Netherlands, and Yugoslavia did not send athletes to Lake Placid.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The **1980 Winter Olympics**, officially the **XIII Olympic Winter Games** and also known as **Lake Placid 1980**, were an international multi-sport event held from February 13 to 24, 1980, in Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid was elected as the host city for the 1980 Winter Games at the 75th International Olympic Committee (IOC) Session in Vienna, Austria, in 1974.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] This marked the second time the Upstate New York village hosted the Winter Games, after 1932.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The only other candidate city to bid for the 1980 games, Vancouver–Garibaldi, withdrew before the final vote.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Some venues from the 1932 Games were renovated for use in the 1980 Games, and events were held at the Olympic Center, Whiteface Mountain, Mt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Van Hoevenberg Olympic Bobsled Run, the Olympic Ski Jumps, the Cascade Cross Country Ski Center, and the Lake Placid High School Speed Skating Oval.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Games were a success in terms of sport, but the organization was criticized because of numerous transport problems.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The 1980 Games were the last to take place in a city of less than 15,000 inhabitants.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Winter Olympics brought together 1,072 athletes from 37 countries to take part in six sports and 10 disciplines comprising a total of 38 official events (one more than in 1976).
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] People's Republic of China, Cyprus, and Costa Rica participated in the Winter Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] American speed skater Eric Heiden set the record for most medals for an athlete in one edition of the Winter Olympic Games after he medaled in all five speed skating events.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Olympic ice hockey tournament saw the young American team defeat the heavily favored Soviet professionals in what became known as the *Miracle on Ice*, on their way to the gold medal.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] In the other disciplines, Soviet Nikolaj Zimjatov won three gold medals in cross-country skiing and the Liechtenstein skier Hanni Wenzel won her country's first two gold medals in alpine skiing.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union finished first in the medal standings, with ten gold medals, while East Germany won the most medals overall, 23.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The United States was third on both counts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] After Lake Placid hosted the 1932 Olympic Winter Games, the community continued to bid on upcoming editions of the Games, submitting seven total bid attempts, including 1948, 1952, and 1956.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Three of these were supported by the United States Olympic Committee and presented to the International Olympic Committee: 1968, 1976, and 1980.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Until 1980, each of the bid attempts failed, either due to falling short of gaining support at the national level, or during the IOC vote.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] When Denver withdrew after being selected to host the 1976 Winter Games, the USOC initially supported Salt Lake City to replace Denver.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] But on January 26, 1973, the Salt Lake City bid collapsed due to unsecured financial backing and discontent by Utah residents.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid and the USOC submitted a late bid to host the 1976 Games to the IOC in February 1973, as there was a risk that the selection process would be canceled due to the lack of interested parties.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The IOC selected Innsbruck, Austria, to host the 1976 Games in place of Denver, with Lake Placid finishing as the runner-up.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] IOC President Lord Killanin later stated that members of the IOC executive favored the Austrian bid as a way to "make peace with the people of Austria" over the decision in 1972 to declare Austrian skiing star Karl Schranz ineligible for the games as a professional athlete.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Undeterred, Lake Placid re-sent the same campaign materials that were originally used for the 1976 bid to the United States Olympic Committee on November 20, 1973, and made the official bid in September 1974.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The United States Olympic Committee, embarrassed by Denver's 1976 withdrawal, required Lake Placid's bid to be widely supported by residents and government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid also secured the support of the environmental groups Sierra Club and Adirondack Mountain Club.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Three other cities declared themselves candidates for the 1980 Winter Games: Vancouver—Garibaldi (Canada), Lahti (Finland), and Chamonix (France).
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The bids for Lahti and Chamonix were withdrawn early in the bid process, and Vancouver (the latter hosted the 2010 games), which was unable to obtain the support of the Government of British Columbia, withdrew its candidacy on October 4, 1974.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The members of the IOC awarded the 1980 Winter Games to Lake Placid on October 23, 1974, during the 75th IOC Session in Vienna.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Games took place in the shadow of the Cold War with a number of other complex international events occurring in the leadup to the games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] In November 1979, sixty-two Americans were taken hostage at the United States embassy in Tehran by Iranian militants, a situation that would not resolve until after the Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] In December 1979, the Soviet Union began the invasion of Afghanistan, which led to United States President Jimmy Carter calling for the international boycott of the 1980 Summer Games in Moscow.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Western governments first considered the idea of boycotting the Moscow 1980 Summer Olympics in response to the situation in Afghanistan at the December 20, 1979, meeting of NATO representatives.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The idea was not completely new to the world: in the mid-1970s, proposals for an Olympic boycott circulated widely among human rights activists and groups as a sanction for Soviet violations of human rights.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] At that time, very few member governments expressed interest in the proposal.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] However, the idea gained popularity in early January 1980 when Soviet nuclear scientist and dissident Andrei Sakharov called for a boycott.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] On January 14, 1980, the Carter Administration joined Sakharov's appeal and set a deadline by which the Soviet Union must pull out of Afghanistan or face the consequences, including an international boycott of the games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] On January 26, 1980, Canadian Prime Minister Joe Clark announced that Canada, like the US, would boycott the Olympic Games if Soviet forces did not leave Afghanistan by February 20, 1980.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Carter also proposed moving the Olympics to Greece on a permanent basis to eliminate the issue of politicization of the Games' hosting, but the IOC rejected the idea.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Ultimately, 66 nations boycotted the 1980 Summer Olympics, but this did not impact the Lake Placid Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Another ongoing international situation was the conflict between the People's Republic of China and Taiwan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Taiwan competed under the name of "Republic of China" and with its national flag until the 1976 Winter Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] In October 1979, the IOC recognized the Olympic Committee of the People's Republic of China after threats from China to withdraw from the Games, and forced Taiwan to take the name "Chinese Taipei" and to adopt a new flag for the 1980 Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The decision was appealed to a Swiss court and was upheld on January 15, 1980.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Taiwanese delegation refused to comply with the IOC's decision and arrived at the Olympic Village with the same flag and the same name as before.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] After being refused entry, the Taiwan team canceled its participation in the Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The People's Republic of China, which threatened to withdraw if Taiwan participated under the name of "Republic of China", took part in its first Olympic Games since 1952 and the first Winter Games in its history.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Olympic Organizing Committee (LPOOC) was established as a not-for-profit corporation in December 1974.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Its board of directors was made up of 48 people, with a 13-member executive board.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Ron MacKenzie, who was instrumental in developing the region and securing the Games, was the chair of the organizing committee when it was founded.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] He died in December 1978, fourteen months before the start of the Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Bernard Fell was the chairman of the board of directors and Art Devlin was the vice-chairman.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The LPOOC's vision for the Games was a simple Games that would return to the basics of the Olympic movement.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The budget for the 1980 Winter Olympic Games grew from an initial projection of US$30 million, to a total of US$168.7 million.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The cost of the games was financed by three parties, the federal government ($82.7 million), the State of New York ($32.4 million), and the organizing committee ($53.6 million).
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] In the 2016 study of cost overruns at Olympic Games at Oxford University, researchers found the Lake Placid Winter Olympic Games had the largest cost overruns of any Winter Games at 324 percent above the planned cost.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The budget overruns were attributed to environmental protection measures, additional work undertaken to modernize existing facilities, overly optimistic cost estimates, and inflation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Games ended with a deficit of $8.5 million.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] After a request for funds and the authorities' refusal, the organizing committee saw no other option but to declare bankruptcy, but in January 1981 the Governor of New York announced that the remaining deficit would be paid by New York State.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Additional costs included transport improvements totaling $4.8 million, the extension of the electricity and hydroelectric network at $2.7 million, and construction for the headquarters of the New York State Police at $3.8 million.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] In addition, $8 million was allocated for security costs.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The expenses of the organizing committee were mainly administrative totaling $48.1 million.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The increasing costs for the Games and charges of nepotism and mismanagement resulted in a federal auditor investigating the LPOOC.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Public questions regarding accounting practices and contract awards resulted in the LPOOC's marketing director being replaced.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Further scrutiny came when another director was asked to resign when it became public that the individual had not filed income taxes for a number of years.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The company awarded the food management contract for the Games came under federal investigation for associations with organized crime.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Revenue for the LPOOC came primarily from sponsorship contracts signed with more than 200 companies totaling around $30 million in cash, goods or services, and from the sale of broadcasting rights totaling $21 million and included $8 million donated to the IOC.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Around 550,000 tickets were distributed for the 1980 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Ticket distribution to the public included different regions of the United States (65.8%), Canada (6%), and other countries (8.2%).
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The remainder was distributed among sponsors and suppliers (8.7%), the US Olympic Committee, the organizing committee, authorities, donors, and authorized companies (10.1%), or kept in reserve (1.2%).
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The public prices for tickets ranged from $15 to $70.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Security for the Lake Placid Winter Games was provided by the New York State Police and 26 other agencies including the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The organizing committee also hired the private security company Pinkerton National Detective Agency.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The security headquarters were located at Ray Brook, which also was the site of the Olympic Village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Police officers were trained in hostage negotiation techniques and various sensors were installed to detect any terrorist attack.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] A four-meter double barrier was erected surrounding the Olympic Village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Winter Games were plagued with transportation problems complicating the planning and operations of the Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The small mountain community did not have the accommodations or resources to handle the expected 50,000 spectators each day.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Most of the accommodations within the community were reserved for Games officials and athletes' families, meaning spectators commuted as much as ninety miles (140 km) daily to attend events.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Anticipating these challenges, the LPOOC prohibited private cars from entering Lake Placid for the duration of the Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Instead the LPOOC provided parking and a shuttle system to transport spectators to the competition venues, and hired 60 taxis and 300 coaches, instead of the 450 initially planned, to be available to athletes, coaches, officials, and VIPs.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The first evidence that the Games would be plagued with transportation issues came a year earlier, at the pre-Olympic ski jumping competition in February 1979, which saw spectators create an eleven-mile (18 km) traffic jam.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Once the Games started, the inadequate transportation planning was evident quickly as American and Soviet athletes arrived late for the opening ceremony.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Throughout the Games, the main street of Lake Placid was often blocked by traffic jams, and journalists, spectators, and athletes found long waits at bus stops.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Spectators were often left stranded, either missing events or unable to return home from events.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] After five days, Governor Hugh Carey declared a partial state of emergency to address the issues.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The LPOOC attributed the transportation challenges to, among other things, the lack of communication with transport companies and the state government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The emblem of the 1980 Olympic Winter Games contained several symbols.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The right part was reminiscent of the mountains surrounding Lake Placid and the left part was a stylized Ionic column that referred to the Ancient Olympics.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The indentation at the top of the column represented two basins symbolizing the two editions of the Games organized in Lake Placid.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] On the Games poster, the Olympic rings overhung this emblem.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The former Will Rogers Memorial Hospital was briefly used as press headquarters.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The site was considered ideal for the available infrastructure from the 1932 Winter Olympics, most notably the Bobsleigh run.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The existing facilities meant the Olympics could be staged on a reasonable budget and with limited environmental impact.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] It was not just a matter of convenience, either, according to Lake Placid's congressman, Representative Robert McEwen.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] "It is no secret to us in America that the measure of federal support given to athletes in Communist countries (so that they win medals and improve the countries' image abroad) is on a level unknown to us here in America," he told Congress.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The local Olympic committee needed congressional approval for funding to build the Olympic Village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Congress required an after-use contract for facilities, and it was agreed that the Olympic Village would be built in accordance to Federal Bureau of Prisons needs.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Following the Olympic Games, it was repurposed for Federal Correctional Institution, Ray Brook.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1980 Winter Games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Cyprus made its Olympic debut at the games.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The People's Republic of China and Costa Rica both made their Winter Olympic debut.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The Republic of China refused to attend both the Summer Games in Montreal, the Winter Games in Lake Placid, and the Summer Games in Moscow over the IOC's recognition of the People's Republic of China as "China", and its request for the Republic of China to compete as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The PRC, on the other hand, returned to the Olympics for the first time since 1952 and made its Winter Olympic debut, although it then boycotted the 1980 Moscow Summer Olympics.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] Roni was the Olympic mascot of the Games, created by Don Moss.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The mascot was a raccoon, which is a familiar animal from the mountainous region of the Adirondacks where Lake Placid is situated.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The name Roni came from the word *raccoon* in Iroquoian, the language of the native people from the region of the State of New York and Lake Placid, and was chosen by Lake Placid school children.
[src:adirondack-mountains/1980-winter-olympics] The official theme song for the 1980 Winter Olympics was "Give It All You Got" by the American flugelhorn player Chuck Mangione, who performed the song (along with the song "Piña Colada") live at the Closing Ceremony, with the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra (Canada).
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The number of abortion clinics in New York (for which more than half of all patient visits are for abortion) declined from 302 in 1982 to 95 in 2014, but increased to 113 in 2017, according to Guttmacher Institute.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The abortion rate decreased from an estimated 39 abortions per 1000 women aged 15–44 in 1992 to 22 per 1000 in 2016, according to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Madame Restell opened a business that performed abortions in the 1830s in New York City.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Her business remained open for around 35 years, and openly advertised its services in newspapers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] She had branches in several other cities, including Boston and Philadelphia, and employed traveling agents working for the company that sold her "Female Monthly Pills".
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] New York state saw many women dying during the 1860s and 1870s due to using unskilled abortion providers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Some of these deaths were highly publicized, which turned the public's attitude against abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1918, Margaret Sanger was charged under the New York law against disseminating contraceptive information.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On appeal, her conviction was reversed because contraceptive devices could legally be promoted to cure and prevent disease.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] A group of science, health, and medical experts met in 1955 in New York; their purpose was to discuss abortion in the United States.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Their belief was that between 200,000 and 1.2 million illegal abortions took place annually.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Planned Parenthood Federation of America had a conference at Arden House in New York in 1955.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The conference's purpose was to review the knowledge framework in the United States as it related to abortion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] One of the accomplishments of the conference was that it published the "first objective and quantitative estimates of illegal abortions".
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The conference also provided participants with a first-hand perspective on the state of abortion in the country, from a presentation by a physician who had performed over 5,000 abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1955, Sloane Hospital in New York created a hospital review board to approve all abortion requests.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Consequently, the number of abortions performed at the hospital in the next five-year period for therapeutic reasons was half what it was prior to 1955.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] At Harlem Hospital, before the legalization of abortion in New York in 1970, there was a positive correlation between neonatal and perinatal mortality and the number of clandestine and non-medical community abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In the 1940s and 1950s, abortions would be given to some women on mental health waivers at Mount Sinai if they indicated they had attempted to commit suicide as a result of the pregnancy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] At one New York City hospital, in the pre-*Roe v.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Wade* period, a teenage girl asked for an abortion, citing suicide attempts as the reason; the hospital committee initially turned her down and hospitalized her, and the girl continued to try to kill herself.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The waiver was finally granted, in order to stop the disruption the girl caused at the hospital.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Because of the nature of their abortion laws, New York City and the District of Columbia became destination centers for women in 1971 who were seeking legal abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Abortion was legalized up to the 24th week of pregnancy in New York in 1970, three years before it was legalized for the entire United States with the Supreme Court's decision in *Roe v.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Wade* was later overturned in 2022 by the Supreme Court in *Dobbs v.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The first statute to criminalize abortion in New York State was enacted in 1827.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] This law made post-quickening abortions a felony, and made pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] New York later allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] New York was the first state to create a therapeutic exemption that allowed women to have abortions if their life was at risk by continuing the pregnancy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1845, New York passed a statute that said women who had abortions could be given a prison sentence of three months to a year.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] They were one of the few states at the time to have laws punishing women for getting abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Susannah Lattin's death led to an investigation that resulted in regulating maternity clinics and adoptions in New York City in 1868.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1872, New York state made it a penalty to perform an abortion, with a criminal sentence of between 4 and 20 years in prison.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The New York State legislature amended their abortion-related statute in 1965 to allow for more therapeutic exceptions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On April 10, 1970, the New York Senate passed a law legalizing abortion until the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Rockefeller signed the bill into law the next day.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] At the time, New York State was a Republican "trifecta", meaning both chambers of the legislature and the governorship were Republican-controlled.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] First, it added a consent provision requiring a physician to obtain the woman's consent before performing an abortion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Second, it permitted physician-provided elective abortion services within the first 24 weeks of pregnancy, or to preserve the woman's life.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Third, it permitted a woman, when acting upon the advice of a duly licensed physician, to perform an "abortional act" on herself within the first 24 weeks of pregnancy, or to preserve her life.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] New York was the second state, after Hawaii, to enact landmark abortion law legislation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Unlike Hawaii, however, New York's abortion law did not have a 90-day residency requirement.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Between 1970 and 1973, the New York General Assembly attempted to repeal their law that made abortion legal.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Governor Rockefeller successfully vetoed the repeal attempt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The law went into effect January 1, 2016.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The state legislature was one of five states nationwide that tried, and failed, to pass a "fetal heartbeat" bill in 2014.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The terminology of these bills is largely contested, and considered to be inaccurate by medical professionals.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] This is because at the proposed time (as early as 6 weeks), the conceptus is not yet considered a fetus, and is actually an embryo.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Additionally, there is no heart present in the embryo; it would more accurately be called a cluster of cells with electrical activity.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] As of May 14, 2019, the state prohibited abortions after the fetus was viable, generally some point between week 24 and 28.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] This period uses a standard defined by the US Supreme Court in 1973, with the *Roe v.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions, except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In November 2024, New York voters passed a referendum to amend the state constitution to protect the right to abortion. and will take effect on January 1, 2025.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The US Supreme Court's decision in 1973's *Roe v.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Wade* ruling meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] However, the Supreme Court overturned *Roe v.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, No.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Pro-Choice Network of Western New York* was before the US Supreme Court in 1997.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Two abortion clinics in western New York had obtained injunctions to prevent anti-abortion rights protesters from blockading their facilities, or engaging in other types of disruptive protests.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The Court ruled in a 6–3 decision that "floating buffer zones" preventing protesters approaching people entering or leaving abortion clinics were unconstitutional, though "fixed buffer zones" around the clinics themselves remained constitutional.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The Court's upholding the fixed buffer was the most important aspect of the ruling, because it was a common feature of injunctions nationwide.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In the 1940s, police would raid suspected illegal abortion clinics.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state decreased by thirteen, going from 302 in 1982 to 289 in 1992.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The number of abortion providers in New York was 266 in 1996.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In the period between 1992 and 1996, the state ranked third in the loss of number of abortion clinics, losing 23 to have a total of 266 in 1996.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2008, the states with the most providers were California with 522 and New York with 249.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2014, there were 95 abortion clinics in New York, and 44% of the counties in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] That year, 10% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a county without an abortion clinic.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2017, there were 58 Planned Parenthood clinics, of which 49 offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 4,718,933 women aged 15–49.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] A study was done involving 300 women approached by anti-abortion protesters at an abortion clinic in Buffalo, New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] It found that while some women were upset by the protesters, none of the 300 women changed their minds as a result of protester's actions in relation to their decision to get an abortion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1972, an estimated 100,000 women traveled to New York to have legal abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Over half of them traveled more than 500 miles to get a legal abortion in the state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1990, 2,443,000 women in the state had a reported unintended pregnancy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The highest number of legal induced abortions by the state in 2000 occurred in New York (94,466), while Florida was second (88,563), and Texas was third (76,121).
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2001, New York had the highest number of induced abortions (91,792), while Idaho had the lowest induced abortion to live birth ratio, at 36 per 1,000 live births.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2010, the state of New York had 45,722 publicly funded abortions, of which none were federally funded and all were state-funded.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] State abortion estimates differ depending on the data source (US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) versus the Guttmacher Institute).
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2012, New York City reported abortions (31,328) outnumbered live births (24,758) for black children.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Black and Hispanic abortions combined (54,245) account for 73% of the total abortions in the city in 2012, according to a report by the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene, Office of Vital Statistics.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 2013, among white women aged 15–19, there were 2,660 abortions, 5,860 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 4,670 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 760 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Seventeen states, including New York, use their own funds to cover all or most "medically necessary" abortions sought by low-income women under Medicaid, thirteen of which are required by state court orders to do so.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In the 1920s, women in the New York City metro area would sometimes try to induce abortions using botulism.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In some cases, doctors would refuse to treat women who were suspected of attempting abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Mary Parker of Brooklyn died after her illegal abortion in 1929, and left behind three children.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Her cause of death was listed as gangrene, not botulism poisoning.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Around 1947, a young nurse and her boyfriend with some medical training borrowed an apartment in New York City from friends.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] While the friends were gone, the boyfriend performed an illegal abortion on his girlfriend, leaving blood on the floor and kitchen table.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] During the 1940s and 1950s, nurses attended to women in Bellevue Hospital who were admitted after botched abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] These dying women often gave evidence to the police about the procedures in order to prosecute people performing illegal abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] A few women withheld the names of the abortion providers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In the 1960s, a woman named Mason attending Ohio State visited a Planned Parenthood clinic to seek information on getting an abortion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] At the time, the Ohio-based clinic was providing information on birth control and offering reproductive health care.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] They referred her to a clinic in New York City, who told her that the procedure would cost around US$150.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] With help from her boyfriend and her best friend, she worked covertly to raise the money for the procedure; she stole glass bottles from a neighbor, so she could turn them in for US$0.05 a piece to fund her abortion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Her friend also collected glass bottles from her own mother to raise money for the abortion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Mason and her boyfriend then drove through the night to Manhattan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] She attributes her ability to obtain an abortion to geography.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Then 18-year-old Connecticut resident Vikki Wachtel traveled to New York City to obtain an abortion at Bellevue Hospital in October 1970, where she had post-abortion complications.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Her abortion took place 5 months after New York State legalized the procedure.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] She said that bans would make abortions more dangerous.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Christine Marinoni had an abortion in 2010.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] She made the decision with her wife, Cynthia Nixon, after doctors told the couple that the fetus Marinoni was carrying was not viable.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1962, around 1,200 women were admitted to hospitals in New York City's Harlem Hospital as a result of incomplete attempted abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In the period between 1972 and 1974, Texas and New York State had the largest number of illegal abortion deaths.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Texas recorded 14 in this period, while New York had 11 in a period where 63 deaths from illegal abortions were reported nationwide.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1972, New York had 10 illegal abortion deaths.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1974, the state recorded no illegal abortion deaths.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The deaths in the District of Columbia and New York in this period demonstrated that even where abortion is legal, women face circumstances that drive them to have irregular, non-physician-assisted abortions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] There are a variety of factors for this, including lack of education, poverty, and distrust of the medical establishment.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Susannah Lattin was an American woman who died of a postpartum infection at an illegal maternity clinic at 6 Amity Place in New York City, operated by Henry Dyer Grindle.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Houghton, a clerk at Whitehouse's boot and shoe store on Fulton Street, Brooklyn.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Harrison to perform an abortion, but Lattin did not go through with it.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] She was still hoping that Houghton would marry her.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Houghton then quit his job and moved to Philadelphia to escape the situation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Lattin next went to her cousin, George H.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Powell, who worked as a butcher at the Washington Market.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Powell pretended to be her husband and arranged for her, as "Mrs Smith", to see Dr Henry D.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Grindle, who ran an unauthorized "lying-in" hospital that allowed the pregnant woman to have their children and have them illegally adopted.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The doctor wanted her to pay $150, but she could only pay $100 and he accepted it.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Lattin checked into the lying-in hospital on August 5, 1868; then, a few weeks later, she delivered a healthy baby boy who was adopted anonymously, without any record kept of the adoptive parents.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Around August 18, 1868, she developed a postpartum infection.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The medical student who attended to her realized Lattin was in serious condition and was not likely to survive, and he persuaded her to tell him her real name, so he could notify her family.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] The message got to her parents after she had died.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1990, John O'Connor, archbishop of New York, suggested that, by supporting abortion rights, Catholic politicians risked excommunication.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Congresswoman Nancy Pelosi said that, "There is no desire to fight with the cardinals or archbishops.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Café Altro Paradiso in New York City held a fund-raiser for Planned Parenthood on May 19, 2019, to support the organization's abortion services.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Since 2018, NYC For Abortion Rights has held a counter-protest to an anti-abortion protest in Manhattan on the first Saturday of every month.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Wade on June 24, 2022, AM New York Metro estimated that 17,000 protesters gathered in Washington Square Park, in New York City, to demonstrate against the ruling, with thousands more in Union Square.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Others were spread throughout Grand Central Station, Bryant Park, and city streets.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On July 7, an anti-abortion protester was charged with disorderly conduct for allegedly preventing access to a clinic in Hempstead, and an abortion rights rally in support of the clinic was held on July 21 in Mineola.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On December 3, seven people were arrested when anti-abortion protesters clashed with abortion rights protesters outside of a clinic in Manhattan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On February 4, 2023, anti-abortion protesters clashed with abortion rights protesters outside of a clinic in Manhattan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On May 6, 2023, four people were arrested after anti-abortion protesters clashed with abortion rights protesters outside of St.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On March 23, 2024, 7 people were arrested during an abortion rights counter-protest of an anti-abortion march in Manhattan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On September 28, 2024, a rally and vigil for Amber Thurman and Candi Miller was held in Washington Square Park in Manhattan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] On November 9, 2024, an anti-Trump rally was held in Manhattan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver, through the U.S. mail, any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, or the prevention of conception or venereal disease, even to medical students.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] In April 1992, anti-abortion activists organized the "Spring of Life" protests in Buffalo.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] This was one of three large anti-abortion protests that received extensive media coverage.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] There was an arson attack at an abortion clinic in New York in 1979 that caused around US$250,000 in damage.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] An incident of anti-abortion violence occurred at an abortion clinic in New York City on December 10, 1985.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Another occurred at an abortion clinic in Syracuse, New York, on May 23, 1990.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Another act of violence happened at an abortion clinic in Buffalo, New York, on April 18, 1992.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] David Gandell of Rochester, New York, sustained serious injuries on October 28, 1997, after being targeted by a sniper firing through a window in his home.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Between 1993 and 2015, 11 people were killed at American abortion clinics.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Barnett Slepian was shot to death with a high-powered rifle at his home in Amherst, New York, on October 23, 1998.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] His was the last in a series of similar shootings against providers in Canada and northern New York state which were all likely committed by James Kopp.
[src:adirondack-mountains/abortion-in-new-york] Kopp was convicted of Slepian's murder after being apprehended in France in 2001.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The **Adirondack High Peaks** are a set of 46 mountain peaks in the Adirondack Mountains of New York state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] They have been popular hiking destinations since the late 1920s, when the list of peaks was published in Russell Carson's book *Peaks and Peoples of the Adirondacks*.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Those who have climbed all 46 High Peaks are eligible to join the Adirondack Forty-Sixers club.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The list of peaks was originally compiled by the mountaineers Herbert Clark, Bob Marshall, and George Marshall, with input from Russell Carson.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The Marshall brothers wished to climb every notable peak in the Adirondacks, which they accomplished with Clark between 1918 and 1925.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The criteria used were that all peaks should be at least 4,000 feet (1,200 m) in elevation and either have 300 feet (91 m) of prominence or 0.75 miles (1.21 km) of distance from another peak.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Later surveys revealed that Blake Peak, Cliff Mountain, Couchsachraga Peak, and Nye Mountain are under 4,000 feet in elevation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] A survey in the mid-20th century measured the elevation of MacNaughton Mountain as exactly 4,000 feet (1,219 m), but a more recent survey listed the mountain at 3,983 feet (1,214 m).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] No mountains have been removed or added to the list since the 1920s due to tradition.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] All but four of the peaks are located in central and northern Essex County, primarily south of Lake Placid and Keene Valley.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The others are just to the west in Franklin County.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] All of the summits are on land owned by New York State as part of its Forest Preserve.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] 42 are in a vast tract of nearly 300,000 acres (1,200 km2) known as the High Peaks Wilderness Area, subdivided into central (26 peaks) and outer (16 peaks) zones.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Nine of the peaks in the outer zone are in an area formerly known as the Dix Mountain Wilderness Area, which was added to the High Peaks Wilderness in 2018.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Giant Mountain and Rocky Peak Ridge are in the adjacent Giant Mountain Wilderness Area.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Whiteface Mountain and Esther Mountain are north of Lake Placid in the Wilmington Wild Forest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] There are many mountain ranges within the High Peaks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The Dix Range includes five out of the forty-six High Peaks: Macomb, Grace Peak, South Dix, Hough, and Dix Mountain.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The Great Range includes seven out of the forty-six High Peaks: Lower Wolfjaw, Upper Wolfjaw, Armstrong, Gothics, Saddleback, Basin, and Haystack.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The Seward Range includes four out of the forty-six High Peaks: Seward, Donaldson, Emmons, and Seymour Mountain.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The MacIntyre Range includes four out of the forty-six High Peaks: Mount Marshall, Wright, Algonquin and Iroquois.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The Santanoni Range includes three out of the forty-six High Peaks: Santanoni, Panther, and Couchsachraga.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The region contains many alpine lakes and meadows, wetlands, streams, and forests.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Atop the highest peaks, above the tree line, lies a small alpine ecosystem, a remnant of a larger lowland tundra that retreated uphill following the most recent period of glaciation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The amount of this ecosystem is constantly changing due to variation in the climate from year to year, and has been estimated by different methods to only cover between 65–85 acres (26–34 ha).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The alpine ecosystem is considered extremely fragile to damage from hikers, and the Adirondack Mountain Club launched an education campaign to avoid further damage in the 1970s, since which some peaks have seen documented recovery.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The Eastern High Peaks Wilderness area is the most regulated area.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Fires are not permitted; dogs must be leashed; overnight groups are limited to eight people and day groups to 15; and bear-resistant food canisters are required from April through November.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Camping is prohibited above any elevation greater than 4,000 feet on any of the Adirondack High Peaks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Of the two highest peaks, Algonquin Peak is regarded as a more challenging hike than Mount Marcy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] Twenty of the peaks have no official trail to the top, although rough informal routes, commonly referred to as "herd paths," have developed over the years.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] No true bushwhacking is required on any of the peaks, although some trails are still quite primitive.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-high-peaks] The summit of Whiteface Mountain can alternatively be reached by motor vehicle on the Whiteface Mountain Veterans' Memorial Highway.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The **Adirondack Mountain Club** (**ADK**) is a nonprofit organization founded in 1922.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The ADK is dedicated to the protection and responsible recreational use of the New York State Forest Preserve, parks, wild lands, and waters; it conducts conservation, and natural history programs.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] There are 27 local chapters in New York and New Jersey.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The club has worked to increase state holdings in the Adirondack Park and to protect the area from commercial development.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The idea of forming the ADK was conceived by Meade C.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Pratt, Conservation Commissioner of New York State, and William G.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Howard, Superintendent of Forests, Dobson invited other like-minded individuals to an organizational meeting.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The initial meeting, attended by 40 people, took place on December 5, 1921, in the log cabin atop the Abercrombie & Fitch sporting goods store in New York City.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] An organization committee was formed, including representatives of outing, recreational, educational, government, and business interests.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The club's objectives were to develop and maintain hiking trails, to construct and maintain campsites and permanent camps, to publish trail maps and guidebooks, and to educate the public regarding the conservation of natural resources and prevention of forest fires.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] In its early years when there were few trails, ADK supplemented the work of the New York State Conservation Department by clearing and marking 140 miles of trails.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] One of the first trails constructed by club members was the 133-mile Northville-Placid Trail which traverses the Adirondacks in a north-south orientation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Gifford Pinchot, first chief of the U.S.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Forest Service, was an early member, and Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt were life members of the ADK.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The Adirondack Mountain Club has worked to make sites more accessible.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] In August 2023, they opened two accessible sites at the Wilderness Campground at Heart Lake.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Beginning in 2020, the group planned to work on the Long Trail up Mt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Jo, and in October 2023, they finished their work on the new trail.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] On October 14, the ADK had a ribbon cutting ceremony and 50 members hiked up the trail to celebrate.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The trail is near Lake Placid, and more than 18,000 visitors come to the trail annually, which led to the trail needing restoration.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The trail restoration was funded by the Regional Office of Sustainable Tourism Local Enhancement and Advancement Fund.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] The club maintains two lodges, the Adirondak Loj in North Elba and the Johns Brook Lodge in Keene Valley, which provide bunkrooms and private rooms, and communal meals as well as campsites.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Johns Brook, at the foot of the Great Range, is accessible only by hiking, with the easiest route being a 3.5-mile (5.6 km) hike from Keene Valley.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] ADK offers extensive programming all across New York State all year around.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountain-club] Activities include hiking, biking, paddling, snowshoeing, skiing and much more.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The **Adirondack Mountains** (/ˌædɪˈrɒn.dæk/ *ad-i-RON-dak*) are a massif of mountains in Northeastern New York State which form a circular dome approximately 160 miles (260 km) wide and covering about 5,000 square miles (13,000 km2).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The region contains more than 100 peaks, including Mount Marcy, which is the highest point in New York at 5,344 feet (1,629 m).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Adirondack High Peaks, a traditional list of 46 peaks over 4,000 feet (1,200 m), are popular hiking destinations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] There are over 200 named lakes with the number of smaller lakes, ponds, and other bodies of water reaching over 3,000.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Among the named lakes around the mountains are Lake George, Lake Placid, and Lake Tear of the Clouds.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The region has over 1,200 miles (1,900 km) of rivers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Although the mountains are formed from ancient rocks more than 1 billion years old, geologically, the mountains are relatively young and were created during recent periods of glaciation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Because of this, the Adirondacks have been referred to as "new mountains from old rocks".
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] It is theorized that there is a hotspot beneath the region, which causes continued uplift at the rate of 0.06 to 0.12 inches (1.5 to 3 mm) annually.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Adirondack mountain range has such unusual characteristics compared to the area around it that it is divided into its own province within the Appalachian Highlands physiographic division.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] It is bounded by three other provinces: the St.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Lawrence (Champlain) on the north, northeast; the Appalachian Plateau to the south, southwest; and the Valley and Ridge to the southeast.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The entire region lies within Adirondack Park, a New York state protected area of over 6,000,000 acres (2,400,000 ha).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The park was established in 1892 by the state legislature to protect the region's natural resources and to provide recreational opportunities for the public.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] It covers over 20 percent of New York state's land area.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The word Adirondack is thought to come from the Mohawk word *atirǫ́·taks* meaning "eaters of trees".
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The earliest written use of the name was in 1635 by Harmen Meyndertsz van den Bogaert in his Mohawk to Dutch glossary, found in his *Journey into Mohawk Country*.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] He spelled it *Adirondakx* and said that it stood for Frenchmen, meaning the Algonquians who allied with the French.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Another early use of the name, spelled *Rontaks*, was in 1729 by French missionary Joseph-François Lafitau.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] He explained that the word was used by the Iroquois as a derogatory term for groups of Algonquians who did not practice agriculture and therefore sometimes had to eat tree bark to survive harsh winters.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] In 1838, the mountains were named *Adirondacks* by Ebenezer Emmons, the State Geologist for the northern New York State Geological District.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Mohawks themselves referred to the mountains as *Tsiiononteskowa*, meaning 'big mountains'.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Oneida meanwhile, used the word *Latilu·taks*, which meant 'they're eating the trees/beaver'.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The first humans to live in the Adirondacks were Paleo-Indians who arrived around the 14th millennium BC following the end of the Last Glacial Period.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The earliest migrants arrived from the St.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Lawrence River Valley to the north, and settled along the shores of the Champlain Sea.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] During the Archaic Period (8000–1000 BC) this semi-nomadic hunter-gatherer Laurentian culture inhabited the Adirondacks; evidence of their presence includes a projectile point of red-brown chert found in 2007 at the edge of Tupper Lake.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] During an interval of roughly 11,000 years following the end of the Last Glacial Period, the climate of the Adirondacks gradually warmed, with the area's tundra being replaced by forests that were now able to grow.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] During the transition between the Archaic and Woodland (1000 BC – AD 1000) periods, multiple different groups replaced the Laurentian culture—including the Sylvan Lake, River, Middlesex, Point Peninsula, and Owasco cultures.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] 1 AD, maize and beans were being cultivated in the uplands of the Adirondacks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The first Iroquoian peoples, the Mohawk (or Kanyengehaga) and the Oneida (or Oneyotdehaga), arrived in the Adirondack region between 4,000 and 1,200 years ago.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Both groups claimed the Adirondack Mountains as hunting grounds.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] According to Haudenosaunee historian Rick Hill, the region was considered a 'Dish with One Spoon,' symbolizing shared hunting resources between the groups.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] A group of Algonquian people, known as the Mahicans, also occupied the region, particularly the Hudson River Valley.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] These were the groups that the first European explorers of the area encountered.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] European presence in the area began with a battle between Samuel de Champlain and a group of Mohawks, in what is now Ticonderoga in 1609.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Jesuit missionary Isaac Jogues became the first recorded European to travel through the center of the Adirondacks, as the captive of a Mohawk hunting party, in 1642.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The early European perception of the Adirondacks was of a vast, inhospitable wilderness.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] One map of the area from 1771 shows the region as a blank space in the northeastern corner of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Because local Iroquoian and Algonquian tribes had been decimated first by smallpox and measles in the 1600s, then by wars with encroaching European settlers, there likely were very few people living in the region by the time Pownhall wrote his description.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] It is only relatively recently that numerous archaeological finds have definitively shown that Native Americans were indeed very present in the Adirondacks before European contact, hunting, making pottery, and practicing agriculture.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The European impression of a wild region devoid of human connection set up a narrative about wilderness that would persist through the next 200-some years of the region's history.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] While society's perception of the Adirondacks' value changed, they were always seen as a land of natural resources and physical beauty, not of human history.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] First the area was an inhospitable tangle, then a lucrative store of lumber.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] After the American Revolutionary War, New York State gained ownership of most of the land in the region.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Needing money to discharge war debts, the government sold nearly all the original public acreage about 7 million acres for pennies an acre.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Lumbermen were welcomed to the interior, with few restraints, resulting in massive deforestation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Later, the wilderness character of the region became popular with the rise of the Romantic movement, and the Adirondacks became a destination for those wishing to escape the evils of city life.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Rising concern over water quality and deforestation led to the creation of the Adirondack Park in 1885.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] In 1989, part of the Adirondack region was designated by UNESCO as the Champlain-Adirondack Biosphere Reserve.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] For the more recent human history of the Adirondack region, see Adirondack Park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The rocks of the Adirondack mountains originated about two billion years ago as 50,000-foot (15,000 m) thick sediments at the bottom of a sea located near the equator.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Because of plate tectonics, these collided with Laurentia (the precursor of modern North America) in a mountain-building episode known as the Grenville orogeny.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] During this time the sedimentary rock was changed into metamorphic rock.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] It is these Proterozoic minerals and lithologies that make up the core of the massif.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Adirondacks are thought to be uplifted by a hot spot in the Canadian Shield, in contrast to other mountain ranges in New York which were created in the Alleghenian Orogeny and are a part of the Appalachian chain (not to be confused with the cultural region of Appalachia).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Around 600 million years ago, as Laurentia drifted away from Baltica (European Craton), the area began to be pulled apart, forming the Iapetus Ocean.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Faults developed, running north to northeast, which formed valleys and deep lakes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Examples visible today include the grabens Lake George and Schroon Lake.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] By this time the Grenville mountains had been eroded away and the area was covered by a shallow sea.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Several thousand feet of sediment accumulated on the sea bed.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Trilobites were the principal life-form of the sea bed, and fossil tracks can be seen in the Potsdam sandstone floor of the Paul Smiths Visitor Interpretive Center.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] About 10 million years ago, the region began to be uplifted.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] It has been lifted about 7,000 feet (2,000 m) and is continuing at about 0.08 inches (2 mm) per year, which is greater than the rate of denudation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The cause of the uplift is unknown, but geologists theorize that it is caused by a hot spot in the Earth's crust.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] A recent study has revealed a column of seismically slow materials about 30 to 50 miles (50 to 80 km) deep beneath the Adirondack Mountains, which was interpreted to be the upwelling asthenosphere contributing to the uplift of the mountains.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The occurrence of earthquake swarms near the center of the massif at Blue Mountain Lake may be evidence of this.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Some of the earthquakes have exceeded 5 on the Richter magnitude scale.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Starting about 2.5 million years ago, a cycle of Pleistocene glacial and interglacial periods began which covered the area in ice.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] During the most recent episode, the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered most of northern North America between about 95,000 and 20,000 years ago.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] After this the climate warmed, but it took nearly 10,000 years for a 10,000-foot (3,000 m) thick layer of ice to completely melt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Soils in the area are generally thin, sandy, acidic, and infertile, having developed since the glacial retreat.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The climate is strongly continental, with high humidity and precipitation year-round.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Adirondacks typically experience pleasantly warm, rainy weather in the summer (June–August), with temperatures in the range of 66–73 °F (19–23 °C), cooler than the rest of New York State due to the higher elevation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Summer evenings in the Adirondacks are chilly, with temperatures ranging on average between 45–54 °F (7–12 °C).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Winters (December–March) are long, cold, snowy and harsh, with temperatures ranging from 18 to 23 °F (−8 to −5 °C).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Winter nights are frigid, with temperatures between −2 and 4 °F (−19 and −16 °C).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Spring (April–May) and fall (September–November) are short transitional seasons.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The Adirondack Mountains form the southernmost part of the Eastern forest-boreal transition ecoregion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] They are heavily forested, and contain one of the southernmost distributions of the taiga ecotype in North America.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The forests of the Adirondacks include spruce, pine and deciduous trees.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Lumbering, once an important industry, has been much restricted by the creation of state forest preserve.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Breeding birds include northern forest specialists not found anywhere else in the state, such as boreal chickadees, Canada jays, spruce grouse, black-backed woodpeckers, common loons and crossbills.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Mammals include raccoons, beavers, river otters, bobcats, moose, black bears, and coyotes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Extirpated or extinct mammals that formerly roamed the Adirondacks include the eastern cougar, eastern elk, wolverine, caribou, eastern wolf, and the Canada lynx.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Attempted reintroductions of elk and lynx in the 20th century failed for numerous reasons, including poaching, vehicle collisions, and conservation incompetence.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Nearly 60 percent of the park is covered with northern hardwood forest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Above 2,600 feet (790 meters), conditions are too poor for hardwoods to thrive, and the trees become mixed with or replaced by balsam fir and red spruce.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Above 3,500 feet (1,100 meters) black spruce replace red.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] Higher still, only trees short enough to be covered in snow during the winter can survive.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] A small area on the highest peaks exists above the tree line and has an alpine climate.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] These areas are covered by plants which occupied a large lowland tundra following the most recent period of glaciation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The amount of area covered by this ecosystem changes from year to year due to local climate changes, and has been estimated to only cover between 65–85 acres (26–34 hectares).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-mountains] The alpine ecosystem is considered extremely fragile, and was damaged by hikers prior to a 1970s campaign by the Adirondack Mountain Club to preserve it.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The **Adirondack Park** is the designation for a large area of northeastern New York centered on the Adirondack Mountains.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Like Catskill Park to the south, the area is unusual in the United States because, while the entire area is considered "parkland", about 52 percent of the land within the boundary consists of privately owned inholdings.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The remaining 48 percent is publicly owned by the state as part of the Forest Preserve.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Use of public and private lands in the park is regulated by the Adirondack Park Agency.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The park was established in 1892 for "the free use of all the people for their health and pleasure", and for watershed protection.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] At 6.1 million acres (25,000 km2), it is the largest park in the contiguous United States.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park contains the 46 High Peaks, 2,800 lakes and ponds, 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of rivers and streams, and an estimated 200,000 acres (81,000 ha) of old-growth forests.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It is home to 105 towns and villages, as well as numerous farms, businesses, and a timber-harvesting industry.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The park has a population of 130,000 permanent and 200,000 seasonal residents, and sees over 12.4 million annual visitors.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The inclusion of human communities has been described as one of the most successful experiments in conserving previously developed lands in the industrialized world.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Forest Preserve was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1963.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Before the 19th century, the wilderness was viewed as desolate and forbidding.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] As Romanticism developed in the United States, the view of wilderness became more positive, as seen in the writings of James Fenimore Cooper, Ralph Waldo Emerson, John Muir, and Henry David Thoreau.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The 1849 publication of Joel Tyler Headley's *Adirondack; or, Life in the Woods* triggered the development of hotels and stage coach lines.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] William Henry Harrison Murray's 1869 wilderness guidebook depicted the area as a place of relaxation and pleasure rather than a natural obstacle.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Financier and railroad promoter Thomas Clark Durant acquired a large tract of central Adirondack land and built a railroad from Saratoga Springs to North Creek.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] By 1875, there were more than two hundred hotels in the Adirondacks including Paul Smith's Hotel.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] About this time, the Great Camps were developed.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Following the Civil War, Reconstruction Era economic expansion led to an increase in logging and deforestation, especially in the southern Adirondacks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1870 Verplanck Colvin made the first recorded ascent of Seward Mountain during which he saw the extensive damage done by lumbermen.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] He wrote a report which was read at the Albany Institute and printed by the New York State Museum of Natural History.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1872 he was named to the newly created post of Superintendent of the Adirondack Survey and given a $1000 budget by the state legislature to institute a survey of the Adirondacks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1873 he wrote a report arguing that if the Adirondack watershed was allowed to deteriorate, it would threaten the viability of the Erie Canal, which was then vital to New York's economy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] He was subsequently appointed superintendent of the New York state land survey.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1873, he recommended the creation of a state forest preserve covering the entire Adirondack region.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This forestry law also established a Forest Commission which was charged with care, custody, control and superintendence of the Forest Preserve.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1902, the legislature passed a bill defining the Adirondack Park for the first time in terms of the counties and towns within it.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1912 the legislature further clarified that the park included the privately owned lands within it as well as the public holdings.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The restrictions on development and lumbering embodied in Article XIV have withstood many challenges from timber interests, hydropower projects and large-scale tourism development interests.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Further, the language of the article, and decades of legal experience in its defense, are widely recognized as having laid the foundation for the U.S.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] As a result of the legal protections, many pieces of the original forest of the Adirondacks have never been logged and are old-growth forest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Early in the 1900s, recreational use increased dramatically.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The State Conservation Department (now the Department of Environmental Conservation) responded by building more facilities: boat docks, tent platforms, lean-tos, and telephone and electrical lines.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] With the building of Interstate 87 in the 1960s, private lands came under great pressure for development.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This growing crisis led to the 1971 creation of the Adirondack Park Agency (APA) to develop long-range land-use plans for both the public and private lands within the Blue Line.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In consultation with the DEC, the APA formulated the State Land Master Plan which was adopted into law in 1973.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The plan is designed to channel much of the future growth in the Park around existing communities, where roads, utilities, services, and supplies already exist.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 2008 The Nature Conservancy purchased Follensby Pond – about 14,600 acres (5,900 ha) of private land inside the park boundary – for $16 million.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The group plans to sell the land to the state, which will add it to the forest preserve once the remaining leases for recreational hunting and fishing on the property expire.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The park is managed by two state agencies: the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation, created in 1970 and headquartered in Albany; and the Adirondack Park Agency, created in 1971 and headquartered in Ray Brook.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Noted forest ranger Clarence Petty sat on the commission that recommend the creation of the APA.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This system of management is distinctly different from New York's state park system, which is managed by the Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] According to the State Land Master Plan, state lands are classified.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park Land Use and Development Plan (APLUDP) applies to private land use and development.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It defines APA jurisdiction and is designed to direct and cluster development to minimize impact.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] 49% of the park is privately owned, 45% state owned, and 6% is water.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] State wilderness areas account for 46% of the area of the park which is not private property.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] They are managed like federal wilderness areas.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] These areas are far more affected by nature than humanity, to the extent that the latter is practically unnoticeable, for example virgin forest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] No powered vehicles are allowed in wilderness areas.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The 19,000-acre (77 km2) Saint Regis Canoe Area, presently the only Canoe Area in the park, operates under essentially the same conditions as the Wilderness Areas.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Private organizations are buying land in order to sell it back to New York State to be added to the public portion of the Park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are more than 3,000 lakes and 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of streams and rivers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Many areas within the park are devoid of settlements and distant from usable roads.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The fur trade led to the near-extirpation of the beaver in the park by 1893.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Other species, such as the moose, elk, wolf, and cougar were hunted either for their meat, for sport, or because they were seen as a threat to livestock.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The historical presence in the area of animals such as the Canada lynx, wolverine, and caribou are unclear.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Reintroduction efforts for beaver began around 1904 by introducing the remaining beaver in the Adirondacks to imported Canadian ones, and later, from Yellowstone.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The population quickly grew to around 2000 in roughly ten years, and around 20,000 in 1921, with the addition of beavers in different areas of the park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Although the reintroduction was marked as an ecological success, the elevated beaver population was found to have negative economic impacts on waterways and timber sources.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The introduction of elk to the Adirondacks, a species that is unclear to have ever previously occupied the region, would continue after the late-19th century.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] After two previously failed attempts to introduce elk, in 1903, over 150 elk were reported by the State of New York Forest, Fish, and Game Commission to have been released and surviving in the park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The elk population increased for several years, only to decline and ultimately disappear due to poaching.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] To protect and maintain the elk population in the future, the DeBar Mountain Game Refuge was established within the Forest Preserve.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This act of preserving the species was motivated by hunting purposes rather than an ecological or natural aspect.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Game Refuge was defined by a wire fence, numerous postings, and caretakers employed by the State.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This effort to control nature was also observed in the actions of the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC), work crews who established access roads and water-supply expansion.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] A negative result of the CCC coming to the Park was their trapping and killing of "vermin", which included animals such as hawks, owls, fox, and weasels that preyed on other species sought after by hunters and fishermen.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This proved to have unanticipated ecological consequences (most notably the overpopulation of deer) which were reported by the New York State Conservation Department in 1945.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Ongoing efforts have been made to reintroduce native fauna that had been lost in the park during earlier exploitation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are 53 known species of mammals that live in the park, including raccoons, moose, black bears, coyotes, opossums, beavers, porcupines, fishers, martens, river otters, and bobcats.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Notable birds of prey that breed in the park include the red-tailed hawk, broad-winged hawk, peregrine falcon, osprey, great horned owl, barred owl, northern saw-whet owl, and turkey vulture.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Other notable breeding birds include northern forest specialists like Canada jays, black-backed woodpeckers, boreal chickadees, spruce grouse, palm warblers, and yellow-bellied flycatchers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The park is home to 39 species of amphibians and reptiles.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Frog species include the American bullfrog, American toad, gray treefrog, green frog (*Lithobates clamitans*), mink frog, northern leopard frog, pickerel frog, spring peeper, and wood frog.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] As of June 2025, it is not clear whether all frog populations are stable or will remain stable amid the global decline in amphibian populations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Some species, such as the green frog, pickerel frog, spring peeper, and wood frog, are considered stable or of low conservation concern in the Adirondack area.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] However, multiple species have experienced problems with breeding cycles.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] For example, wood frogs in Adirondack Park experienced die-offs caused by ranavirus in the late 2000s, following a broader trend of disease outbreaks among amphibians in the Northeastern United States.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are 7 species of turtle: Blanding's turtle, the eastern musk turtle (*Sternotherus odoratus*), northern map turtle, painted turtle, common snapping turtle, spotted turtle, and wood turtle (*Glyptemys insculpta*).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The spotted turtle and wood turtle are listed as species of special concern in the state of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] An estimated 7–10 million tourists visit the park annually.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are numerous accommodations, including cabins, hunting lodges, villas and hotels, in and around Lake Placid, Lake George, Saranac Lake, Old Forge, Schroon Lake and the St.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Although the climate during the winter months can be severe, with temperatures falling below −30 °F (−34.4 °C), a number of sanatoriums were located there in the early twentieth century because of the positive effect the air had on tuberculosis patients.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Golf courses within the park border include the Ausable Club, the Lake Placid Club, and the Ticonderoga Country Club.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Many of the Adirondack Mountains, such as Whiteface Mountain (Wilmington), Mt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Pisgah (Saranac Lake), Gore Mountain (North Creek), West Mountain (Glens Falls), Hickory (Luzerne), and Mt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Morris (Tupper Lake) have been developed as ski areas.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Hunting and fishing are allowed in the Adirondack Park, although in many places there are strict regulations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Because of these regulations, the large tourist population has not overfished the area, and as such, the brooks, rivers, ponds and lakes are home to large trout and black bass populations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Although restricted from much of the park, snowmobile enthusiasts can ride on a large network of trails.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park Agency visitor interpretive centers are designed to help orient visitors to the park via educational programs, exhibits, and interpretive trails.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Educational programs are available for school groups as well as the general public.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Wild Center in Tupper Lake offers extensive exhibits about the natural history of the region, including a 1,000-foot-long series of elevated bridges that rise up over the forest on the center's campus.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Many of the exhibits are live and include native turtles, otter, birds, fish and porcupines.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The center, which is open year-round, has trails to a river and pond on its campus.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Experience in Blue Mountain Lake contains an extensive collection about the human settlement of the Park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Six Nation Indian Museum in Franklin has as a mission to provide education about Iroquois (also known as Haudenosaunee) culture, particularly environmental ethics, and to reinforce traditional values and philosophies.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] This is done via artifacts, presentations, and hosted visits.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The 46 highest mountains in the park, known as Adirondack High Peaks, were thought to be over 4,000 feet (1,219 m) when climbed by brothers Robert and George Marshall between 1918 and 1924.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Surveys have since shown that four of these peaks — Blake Peak, Cliff Mountain, Nye Mountain and Couchsachraga Peak — are in fact just slightly under 4,000 feet (1,219 m).
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Some hikers try to climb all of the original 46 peaks, and there is a Forty Sixers club for those who have done so.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Cliffs with rock climbing and ice climbing routes are scattered throughout the park boundaries.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The surface of many of the lakes lies at an elevation above 1,500 ft (457 m); their shores are usually rocky and irregular, and the wild scenery within their vicinity has made them very attractive to tourists.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It is the site of the Adirondack Canoe Classic.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Flatwater and whitewater canoeing and kayaking are very popular.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Hundreds of lakes, ponds, and slow-moving streams link to provide routes ranging from under one mile (1.6 km) to weeklong treks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Whitewater kayaking and canoeing are popular on many free-flowing rivers in the Adirondacks, particularly in the spring.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Whitewater rafting trips are run in the spring on the Moose River near Old Forge.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Raft trips are possible on the Hudson River near North River from April to October, due to dam releases provided by the Town of Indian Lake.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Motorboating is formally restricted on only a few bodies of water.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Park Agency visitor interpretive centers (or VICs) were established in 1989 and 1990.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The centers helped orient visitors to the park via educational programs, exhibits, and interpretive trails.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Educational programs were available for school groups as well as the general public.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Due to state fiscal and budgetary constraints, Governor David Paterson marked the VICs for closure on December 31, 2010, and in 2011, New York State sold both visitor centers to nearby colleges.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Paul Smith's VIC opened in 1989 and in 2011 became the Paul Smith's College VIC, owned and operated by Paul Smith's College.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Located on approximately 2,700 acres (11 km2) in Paul Smiths, New York, near Paul Smith's College, the Paul Smith's College Visitor Interpretive Center has approximately 25 miles of maintained trails.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Throughout the property visitors will encounter every habitat type found in the Adirondack Park except alpine.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Each spring the PSC VIC hosts the Great Adirondack Birding Festival.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Throughout the year visitors can partake of guided interpretive walks, regular outdoor activities, naturalist-led canoe paddles on Barnum Pond, and assorted workshops and programs.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In the winter the trails are open for snowshoeing and cross-country skiing.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Interpretive Center is situated on ESF's Huntington Wildlife Forest, a 15,000-acre (61 km2) biological field station the college has operated in Newcomb since 1932, and also home to the college's Adirondack Ecological Center.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Located on 236 acres (0.96 km2) at the outlet of Rich Lake, the center has approximately three and a half miles of interpretive trails.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Habitats include lakeshore, wetlands, old growth forest, and mixed northern forest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Throughout the year staff conduct naturalist-led trail walks, guided paddles on Rich Lake, and assorted workshops and lectures.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] All trails are open in the winter for snowshoeing; cross-country skiing is permitted, and requires varying degrees of skill depending on trails and conditions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Management and ownership of the Newcomb center was assumed by the SUNY College of Environmental Science and Forestry (SUNY-ESF) on July 1, 2010, with program responsibility beginning January 1, 2011.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] While the park does contain large areas of wilderness, some areas developed to a varying degree.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Interstate 87 or *Northway*, completed in the 1970s, runs north to south through the eastern edge of the park, connecting Montreal to Upstate New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The park is traversed by military training routes of the Air National Guard.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are six business parks in Essex County, of which two have certified shovel ready sites.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are many maple syrup producers, and their work is documented at the American Maple Museum at Croghan.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Educational institutions include the State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry and Paul Smith's College.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Railways were used extensively from about 1871 to the 1930s for passenger transport and freight.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Passenger transport was supplemented by stagecoaches.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The principal rail company to the major resorts was the New York Central Railroad.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Destinations within the park, served by its *Adirondack Division*, included Loon Lake, Saranac Lake, Lake Placid, Santa Clara, Tupper Lake, Thendara, Old Forge, and Lake Clear.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] On the edge of the park boundary were Brandon and St.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] North of the park were Moira and Malone.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1920 there were 10 scheduled daily passenger train stops in Big Moose.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Starting in the 1930s, people began to use automobiles rather than the train.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] However, through the 1950s and until 1961, there was a daily day train and a daily night train in each direction to Lake Placid station.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Passenger train service ended on April 24, 1965.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Freight service to and from the Adirondacks also declined after World War II.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Penn Central Transportation Company, successor to the New York Central, continued freight service between Utica and Lake Placid until it abandoned the Remsen-Lake Placid line in 1972.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There are many small airstrips and lakes for seaplanes to land but there is only one commercial airport within the park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack Regional Airport sits just outside of the Village of Saranac Lake in the hamlet of Lake Clear, town of Harrietstown.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The airport's commercial airline service is funded by the government's Essential Air Service program, which provides small communities with flights to major cities that could not be supported without the help of government funding.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Plattsburgh International Airport is located 10 miles (16 km) outside the park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] There is an Adirondack architectural style that relates to the rugged style associated with the Great Camps.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The builders of these camps used native building materials and sited their buildings within an irregular wooded landscape.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] These camps for the wealthy were built to provide a primitive, rustic appearance while avoiding the problems of in-shipping materials from elsewhere.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1903 and 1908 fires consumed nearly 1 million acres (400,000 hectares) of forest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] In 1909, the first Adirondack fire lookout tower, made of logs, was erected on Mount Morris and many others were built over the next several years.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] At one time or another, there have been fire towers at 57 locations in today's Adirondack Park.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The system worked for about 60 years, but has since been replaced by other technologies.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Today, 34 towers survive in the region and many have been restored and are accessible to the public.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Some in the Adirondack Forest Preserve have been listed on the National Register of Historic Places, including those on the following mountains: Arab, Azure, Blue, Hadley, Kane, Loon Lake, Poke-O-Moonshine, St.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] McIntyre Furnace & McNaughton Cottage: an 1853 blast furnace, the 1832 McNaughton Cottage, the remains of the Tahawus Club era buildings, and the early mining-related sites.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Regis Presbyterian church: designed by prolific Saranac Lake architect William L.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Coulter and built on land donated by Paul Smith.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Construction funds came from donations from the congregation, which was largely made up of summer residents.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It served as a church from 1899 to 2010.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Bow Bridge: The Bow Bridge in Hadley is one of only two parabolic or lenticular truss bridges in the region and one of only about 50 remaining in the country.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It was built over the Sacandaga River by the Berlin Iron Bridge Co. in 1885.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Jay Covered Bridge over the Ausable River.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The Adirondack lean-to is a three sided log shelter.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Saranac Village at Will Rogers: a Tudor Revival style retirement community, was constructed in 1930 as a tuberculosis treatment facility for vaudeville performers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Due to the subsequent decline of vaudeville performers, and an eventual cure for tuberculosis, its doors closed in 1975.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] After sitting unused for twenty years, it was bought in 1998 by the Alpine Adirondack Association, LLC and reopened in January 2000 as a retirement community.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Camp Santanoni was once a private estate of approximately 13,000 acres (53 km2), and now is the property of the state, at Newcomb.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It was a residential complex of about 45 buildings.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Now a National Historic Landmark, this is one of the earliest examples of the Great Camps of the Adirondacks.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] At the time of completion in 1893, Camp Santanoni was regarded as the grandest of all such Adirondack camps.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Wellscroft, at Upper Jay, is a Tudor Revival–style summer estate home.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It is a long, 2+1⁄2-story, building with several projecting bays, porches, gables and dormers, a porte cochere and a service wing.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The rear facade features a large semi-circular projection.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The first-story exterior is faced in native fieldstone.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] The interior features a number of Arts and Crafts style design features.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Also on the property are a power house, fire house, gazebo, root cellar, reservoir, ruins of the caretaker's house and carriage house, and the remains of the landscaped grounds.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2004.
[src:adirondack-mountains/adirondack-park] Prospect Point Camp: a Great Camp notable for its unusual chalets inspired by European hunting lodges.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The **administrative divisions of New York** are the various units of government that provide local services in the U.S. state of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The state is divided into boroughs, counties, cities, towns, and villages.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] All of them have their own governments, sometimes with no paid employees, that provide local services.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Centers of population that are not incorporated and have no government or local services are designated hamlets.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Whether a municipality is defined as a borough, city, town, or village is determined not by population or land area, but rather on the form of government selected by the residents and approved by the New York State Legislature.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each type of local government is granted specific home rule powers by the New York State Constitution.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There are still occasional changes as a village becomes a city, or a village dissolves (stops existing), each of which requires legislative action.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] New York also has various corporate entities that provide local services and have their own administrative structures (governments), such as school and fire districts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Almost every piece of land in the state is part of a city or town, which is part of one county.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The exceptions are the city of Geneva; New York City; and ten Indian reservations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] As of 2009, New York has 62 counties (including New York City's five boroughs), which are subdivided into 933 towns and 61 cities (including Geneva in both Ontario and Seneca counties, but excluding New York City and Sherrill).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In total, the state has more than 3,400 active local governments and more than 4,200 taxing jurisdictions.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They do so while adhering to the Constitution of the United States and the Constitution of the State of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Articles VIII (titled "Local Finances") and IX (titled "Local Government", but commonly referred to as the "Home Rule" article) of the state constitution establish the rights and responsibilities of the municipal governments.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The New York State Constitution provides for democratically elected legislative bodies for counties, cities, towns and villages.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] These legislative bodies are granted the power to enact local laws as needed in order to provide services to their citizens and fulfill their various obligations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The county is the primary administrative division of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There are sixty-two counties in the state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Five of the counties are governed as boroughs of the City of New York so do not have separate county governments.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] While originally created as subdivisions of the state meant to carry out state functions, counties are now considered municipal corporations with the power and fiscal capacity to provide an array of local government services.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Such services generally include law enforcement and public safety, social and health services (such as Medicaid), and education (special needs and community colleges).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Every county outside of New York City has a county seat, which is the location of county government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Twenty counties operate under county charters, while 37 operate under the general provisions of the County Law.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Although all counties have a certain latitude to govern themselves, "charter counties" are afforded greater home rule powers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The charter counties are Albany, Broome, Chautauqua, Chemung, Dutchess, Erie, Herkimer, Monroe, Nassau, Oneida, Onondaga, Orange, Putnam, Rensselaer, Rockland, Schenectady, Suffolk, Tompkins, Ulster, and Westchester.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Sixteen counties are governed through an assembly with the power of a board of supervisors, composed of the supervisors of its constituent towns and cities.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In most of these counties, each supervisor's vote is weighted in accordance with the town's population in order to abide by the U.S.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Supreme Court mandate of "one person, one vote".
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Other counties have legislative districts of equal population, which may cross municipal borders; these counties may also have an elected County Executive.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Most counties in New York do not use the term "Board of Supervisors." 34 counties have a County Legislature, six counties have a Board of Legislators, and one county has a Board of Representatives.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The five counties, or boroughs, of New York City are governed by a 51-member City Council.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In non-charter counties, the legislative body exercises executive power as well.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Although the legislature can delegate certain functions and duties to a county administrator, who acts on behalf of the legislature, the legislature must maintain ultimate control over the actions of the administrator.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Many, but not all, charter counties have an elected executive who is independent of the legislature; the exact form of government is defined in the County Charter.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In New York, each city is a highly autonomous incorporated area that, with the exceptions of New York City and Geneva, is contained within one county.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Cities in New York are classified by the U.S.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They provide almost all services to their residents and have the highest degree of home rule and taxing jurisdiction over their residents.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Also, villages are part of a town (or towns; some villages cross town borders), with residents who pay taxes to and receive services from the town.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Cities are neither part of nor subordinate to towns except for the city of Sherrill, which for some purposes is treated as if it were a village of the town of Vernon.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Some cities are completely surrounded by a town, typically of the same name.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There are sixty-two cities in the state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] As of 2000, 54.1% of state residents were living in a city; 42.2% were living in New York City; 11.9% were living in one of the other 61 cities.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In 1686, the English colonial governor granted the cities of New York and Albany city charters, which were recognized by the first State Constitution in 1777.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] All other cities have been established by act of the state legislature and have been granted a charter.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Cities have been granted the power to revise their charters or adopt new ones.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There are no minimum population or area requirements in order to become a city.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] While there is no defined process for how and when a village becomes a city, the Legislature requires clear evidence, usually in the form of a locally drafted charter, that the community in question seeks to incorporate as a city.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The forms of government cities can have are council–manager, strong mayor–council, weak mayor–council or commission.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Forty-six cities, the majority, use the mayor–council form.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The state legislature reorganized government in the area in the 1890s in an effort to consolidate.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Other cities, villages, and towns were annexed to become the "City of Greater New York", (an unofficial term, the new city retained the name of New York), a process basically completed in 1898.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] At the time of consolidation, Queens County was split.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Its western towns joined the city, leaving three towns that were never part of the consolidation plan as part of Queens County but not part of the new Borough of Queens.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] (A small portion of the Town of Hempstead was itself annexed, also.) The next year (1899), the three eastern towns of Queens County separated to become Nassau County.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The city today consists of the entire area of five counties (named New York, Kings, Queens, Bronx, and Richmond).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] While these counties have no county government, boroughs—with boundaries coterminous with the county boundaries—each have a Borough Board made up of the Borough President, the borough's district council members, and the chairpersons of the borough's community boards.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A mayor serves as the city's chief executive officer.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The most populous and largest city in the state is New York City, with a population of over 8.5 million inhabitants and comprising just over 300 sq mi (777.00 km2) of land (468.87 sq mi (1,214.368 km2) total area, which includes water).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The least populous city is Sherrill, New York, with just 3,071 inhabitants in 2010.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The smallest city by area is Mechanicville, New York, which covers 0.91 sq mi (2.4 km2) (of which 0.08 sq mi (0.2 km2) is water).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Several cities, such as Albany, are divided into *wards* for the purposes of municipal representation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each ward elects one member to the city's legislative body, and the wards are redistricted roughly every ten years.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] These divisions can go by other names by city; in Buffalo they are known as *districts*.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] These divisions can either be numbered or named.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] New York City has a unique system of divisions, some of which possess governmental power, see Divisions unique to New York City.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In New York, a town is a municipal corporation, and is the major division of each county (excluding the five boroughs that comprise New York City).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Towns are very similar to townships in other states such as Pennsylvania, Ohio, and Indiana.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Towns in New York are classified by the U.S.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Like New Jersey and southern New England, all of New York is incorporated, meaning all residents who do not live in a city or on an Indian reservation live in a town.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Towns provide or arrange for the primary functions of local government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] While some provide most municipal services for all town residents and selected services for residents of villages, some provide little more than road maintenance.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] As of 2000, 45.8% of state residents were living in a town; 35.9% were living in a town but outside a village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Whereas cities and villages can cross county boundaries, each town in New York is completely contained within a single county.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] New York towns are classified by statute as being a *town of the first class* or a *town of the second class*.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Additionally, a town of the first class can further be classified as a *suburban town* upon meeting certain criteria.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Originally, towns of different classes possessed different powers.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Since 1964, all towns, regardless of classification, have had the same legal powers as were once available only to suburban towns.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Even so, towns of different classifications continue to have organizational differences and certain conditions that must be met before a town's classification changes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The town board serves as the legislative branch.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The supervisor presides over the board, voting on all matters but not possessing veto or tie-breaking power.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Certain towns operate under a town manager form of government, creating an executive branch in the town government, as permitted by legislation enacted in 1976.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] As such, some supervisors have additional authority or executive powers, whereas some towns have town managers or chief executive officers who serve as the executive branch.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] All town justices were originally part of a town's board.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Today, justices belong to a separate judicial branch known as Town Court or Justice Court, part of New York's Justice Court system.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A town may contain one or more villages.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Five towns are coterminous with their single village and share the same name: Green Island in Albany County; East Rochester in Monroe County; and Scarsdale, Harrison, and Mount Kisco in Westchester County.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A sixth, the town of Palm Tree in Orange County was incorporated in 2019 and is coterminous with the village of Kiryas Joel, having acquired land from the town of Monroe.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] When such an entity is formed, officials from either unit of government may serve in both village and town governments simultaneously.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A referendum is held to decide whether residents prefer a village-style or town-style government, which will then function primarily as a village or town but will perform some of the functions of the other form.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Villages remain part of the towns in which they are located; village residents pay both town and village taxes, and vote in both town and village elections.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Towns can contain several hamlets and communities.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] If the United States Postal Service (USPS) has a post office in a hamlet it often will use the name of that hamlet, as will the local fire department or elementary school.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Businesses may also use the name of a hamlet as part of their name.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The United States Census Bureau will, with consideration from the town, designate a census-designated place (CDP) that may use the name of one or more hamlets, though boundaries may differ from what is used by the ZIP code, local fire department, etc.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Towns in New York may be further subdivided into wards, although as of 2017, only fifteen of the state's 932 towns used this system.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In towns operating under the ward system, citizens vote for councilmen who represent a specific area (ward) of the town, as opposed to the at-large councilmen elected in the majority of the state's towns.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The largest town by area is Brookhaven (Suffolk County), which covers 531.5 sq mi (1,377 km2), but more than half of that is water.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The town of Webb (Herkimer County) has the greatest land area, at 451 sq mi (1,170 km2).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The smallest town, Green Island (Albany County), covers 0.7 sq mi (1.8 km2).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The town of Hempstead (Nassau County) has about 760,000 people (2010 census), making it more populous than any city in the state except New York City.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Red House (Cattaraugus County), the least populous, has 38 permanent residents (2010 census).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The use of "town" in a community's name is irrespective of municipal status.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Elizabethtown, Germantown and Stephentown are towns.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Cooperstown, home of the Baseball Hall of Fame, is a village; Jamestown and Middletown are cities; and Levittown is an unincorporated hamlet.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] CDPs are defined collaboratively by state and local officials and the Census Bureau.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They are defined for each census, and it is commonplace to change boundaries and define new CDPs for each census.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The Census Bureau formerly referred to CDPs as "unincorporated places" from 1950 through the 1970 decennial censuses.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The term CDP was first used for the 1980 census, and minimum population criteria for CDPs were dropped with the 2000 census.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Though the term "hamlet" is not defined under New York law, many people in the state use the term hamlet to refer to a community within a town that is not incorporated as a village but is identified by a name, i.e. an unincorporated community.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A hamlet often has a name corresponding to the name of a local school district, post office, or fire district.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Because a hamlet has no government of its own, it depends upon the town or towns that contain it for municipal services and government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Because they do not have governments, hamlets have no clear boundaries.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Suffolk County publishes maps that give hamlet boundaries, but towns within the county also publish maps that conflict both in the number of hamlets and their boundaries.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Nevertheless, all land not within a village is administered by the town.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Most of the rest of New York's hamlets, however, have less well-defined boundaries, and most towns have areas that are not considered to be a part of any hamlet.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The New York State Department of Transportation (NYSDOT) puts hamlet names on rectangular green signs with white lettering at roadside locations of its choosing.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The NYSDOT and local governments also provide community identification signs on some scenic byways to be placed at the roadside boundaries of hamlets, as decided by the sign provider.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Many towns have special zoning or planning districts and planning strategies for their hamlets, and many places welcome signs at the gateways to the hamlets.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Some hamlets are former villages that have dissolved their incorporation (Old Forge in Herkimer County; Rosendale, in Ulster County; and Andes in Delaware County, for example).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Notwithstanding hamlets are not cities or towns, many of them are called out in formal addresses for those residents residing within the limits.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Based on the ZIP Code, the United States Postal Service (USPS) identifies the correct location for mail delivery.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The *New York State Gazetteer*, published by the New York State Department of Health in 1995, includes a list of hamlets in the state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The criteria used for inclusion in the *Gazetteer* are not stated.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The Adirondack Park Agency also uses the term "hamlet", though as a land-use classification for private land under its Adirondack Park Land Use and Development Plan (APLUDP).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The APLUDP extends the boundaries for its classification of hamlets "well beyond established settlements" to allow for growth.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In New York, a village is an incorporated area.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] About 85% of villages fall within a single town.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Villages in the State of New York are classified by the Census Bureau as incorporated places.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Like all municipal corporations, villages have clearly defined legal boundaries.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A village is a municipality that provides services to the residents, services that may or may not include garbage collection, management of cemeteries, street and highway maintenance, street lighting, and building codes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Some villages provide their own police and other municipal services.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Villages have less autonomy than cities.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] While cities are not subject to a town's jurisdiction, villages legally remain part of the town or towns in which they are located.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Village residents pay both town and village taxes, and vote in town and village elections.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Those services not provided by the village are provided by the town or towns containing the village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] As of the 2000 census, 9.9% of the state's population was living in one of the 556 villages in New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The legislature of a village is the board of trustees, composed of a mayor and (usually) four trustees.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The board is responsible for approving mayoral appointments, managing village finances and property, and approving a budget.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The mayor, who is generally the chief executive of the village, may vote in all business before the board and must vote to break a tie.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The mayor generally does not possess veto power, unless this is provided for by local law.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Administrative duties of the mayor include enforcing laws and supervising employees.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A village may also have a full-time village manager who performs these administrative duties instead of the mayor.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In 2007, sixty-seven villages had such a manager.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Some villages have their own village justice, while others utilize the justice of the town or towns in which they are located.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] While most villages are subject to a uniform statewide Village Law, twelve villages operate under charters issued by the state legislature prior to 1874.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Before a revision to the State Constitution in that year, villages were formed by the state legislature through granting of charters.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Many villages reincorporated, dumping their charters in favor of the Village Law.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The villages that retain their charters are Alexander, Carthage, Catskill, Cooperstown, Deposit, Fredonia, Ilion, Mohawk, Ossining, Owego, Port Chester, and Waterford.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] These villages must still comply with those aspects of Village Law that are not inconsistent with their charters.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] To be incorporated, the area of the proposed village must have at least 1,500 inhabitants and not be part of an existing city or village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Additionally, the proposed village can be no more than 5 square miles (13 km2) in area unless its boundaries are to be coterminous with a school, fire, improvement or other district, or the entire town.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The process of incorporation begins with a petition by either 20% of residents or owners of 50% of assessed real property.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] If deemed legally sufficient, incorporation is then voted upon by the qualified voters living in the proposed village only.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Some villages have fewer than 500 residents, having incorporated before the present population requirement or fallen below the old 500-resident threshold after incorporation.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A village may also be dissolved, returning all government control to the town level.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The process of dissolution can be initiated by the village board itself, or upon the submission of a proper petition to the board.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The village board must produce a "dissolution plan" that settles specific matters, such as the village's debts, its employees and property, and the financial impact dissolution would have on village and non-village town residents.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] This plan is voted upon by village voters only.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] About 15% of villages cross other municipal boundaries.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] More than 70 villages are located in two or more towns.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The village of Saranac Lake is in three towns and two counties.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Five towns are coterminous with their single village and have a coterminous town-village form of government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Despite their names, Greenwich Village, the East Village, and Queens Village are not villages, but neighborhoods of the City of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A borough is one of the five major administrative divisions of the consolidated City of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Boroughs do not currently exist elsewhere in the state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each of the five boroughs of the city is coextensive with a county of the state of New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Under New York State's General Municipal Law, a borough results when the towns, villages and cities in a county merge with the county itself.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] This occurred in 1898 when New York City merged with surrounding counties, cities and towns to form its present configuration.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The boroughs were originally intended to retain some local governance in the consolidated city.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each borough individually elects a borough president and used to elect two at-large city council members, in addition to those elected based on each borough's population.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The borough presidents once wielded considerable power as members of the New York City Board of Estimate, but the position is now largely ceremonial and advisory.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Boroughs function as counties for certain purposes, but have no county government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The five New York City district attorneys, however, are still elected by county (for example, the district attorney for Brooklyn is called the Kings County District Attorney).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There are fifty-nine community districts in New York City, each represented by an appointed advisory group called a community board.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each board consists of fifty unpaid members appointed by the borough president.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Half of the members are nominated by the City Council members who represent the area.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The power of the community boards is very limited.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They serve in an advisory capacity regarding land use and zoning, budget, and various concerns of the community.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The boards can recommend action on the part of the city government, but they cannot mandate it.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each is identified by borough name and a number (e.g.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In New York, special purpose units of government provide specialized services only to those who live in the district, and are empowered to tax residents of the district for the services provided in common.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Special districts often cross the lines of towns, villages, and hamlets, and occasionally cities or counties.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] School districts are the most common kind of special district in New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They provide, arrange, or contract for all public education services, including special education and school transportation, the latter also for non-public schools.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] School districts are rarely precisely coextensive with the cities, towns, villages, or hamlets that bear the same name, meaning that a person living in one hamlet or village might send their children to a school associated with a different hamlet or village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Residents pay school taxes to the same school district in which they live and any children living with them attend school.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] All tax-paying residents are eligible for the STAR Program tax rebate, which in effect lessens the value of an individual's primary residence to lessen the tax burden on the residence.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] All but five school districts are separate from municipal governments.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The exceptions are the five cities whose populations exceed 125,000 (Buffalo, New York, Rochester, Syracuse and Yonkers), in which education is part of the municipal budget.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There are five types of school districts in the state, each with slightly different laws.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Common school districts, established in 1812, were the first type of school district in the state.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In July 2004, there were only 11 such districts remaining.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They are not authorized to provide secondary education.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They must, therefore, contract with neighboring school districts to provide high school education for pupils in the district.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Typically one trustee or a three-person board of trustees will govern the district.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In 1853, the legislature established union free school districts, which are districts resulting from a "union" of two or more common school districts, "free" from the restrictions that previously barred them from operating high schools.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In July 2004, there were 163 school districts of this type.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Despite being able to operate high schools, thirty-one of these districts provided only elementary education.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Those districts that are not components of central school districts provide secondary education either by contracting with other districts or being located in one of the three central high school districts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each union free school district is governed by a three- to nine-member board of education.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Central school districts are the most prevalent type of school district in New York.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In July 2004, there were 460 such districts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They began as a result of legislation in 1914.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Central school districts may form from any number (including one) of common, union free, and/or central school districts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Central school districts are permitted to provide secondary education.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Its board of education must consist of five, seven, or nine members and length of service must be three, four, or five years, each decided upon by the voters in the district.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Not to be confused with central school districts, there are only three central high school districts in New York state, all in Nassau County: Bellmore–Merrick Central High School District, Sewanhaka Central High School District, and Valley Stream Central High School District.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Central high school districts provide secondary education to students in two or more common or union free districts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] With creation authorized by the legislature in 1917 and repealed in 1944, creation was reauthorized exclusively for Suffolk County in 1981.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Such districts already established were not affected by the repeal.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] In those cities with populations exceeding 125,000 (New York City, Buffalo, Yonkers, Rochester, and Syracuse), the city school districts are coterminous with the city limits, and education is part of the municipal budget.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] These districts cannot incur debts or levy taxes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The governmental structure in all of these except for New York is that of an elected or appointed board of education.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] New York's public education is headed by a chancellor and has a 13-member all-appointed Department of Education Panel for Education Policy.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The city school districts for the 57 cities having fewer than 125,000 people are separate from the municipal government and are authorized to levy taxes and incur debt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each of them is governed by an elected board of education with five, seven, or nine members.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Districts for smaller cities often extend beyond the city borders and are referred to as "enlarged city school districts", seven of which have reorganized as "central city school districts".
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Owing to the extremely large number (735 in April 2025) of school districts, many of which are quite small, most of them are organized into 37 supervisory districts.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each of these has a Board of Cooperative Educational Services (BOCES).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Each BOCES provides services that are considered difficult for the component school districts to provide on their own, often including special classes for students with disabilities, trades, medical professions such as physical therapy or other specialized classes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Fire districts are public corporations that generally provide fire protection and other emergency response in towns outside villages.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A fire district can levy taxes and incur debt just like other general purpose municipal corporations, although fire districts do not have home rule powers and the taxes are generally collected by the town or towns that the district serves.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Fire districts depend on their towns for initial establishment, expansion of district territory, and dissolution, but are otherwise thereafter autonomous political entities able to exercise only those specific powers granted to them by statute.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The district is governed by a board of elected commissioners.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Villages generally provide their own fire protection, but joint town-village fire districts are permitted.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A Joint Fire District is a fire district that encompasses more than one town, wholly or in part, and may also include a village.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] This is some times done to reduce duplication of services in a small area or to help spread the tax burden when there is a large difference in tax base between neighboring towns.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A joint fire district may also be formed when a fire department in a village that has fire protection districts in the surrounding towns separates itself from the village government to obtain greater self-governance.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] This was seen in 2003 when the fire department in the village of Baldwinsville formed a joint fire district consisting of the village of Baldwinsville and parts of the towns of Lysander and Van Buren in Onondaga County.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] There were 868 fire districts in New York at the end of 2003.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] A fire protection district is established by a town board in order to contract fire protection services with any city, village, fire district or incorporated fire company.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Unlike fire districts, fire protection districts are not authorized to levy property taxes and do not have an independently elected board of commissioners.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The levy to support fire protection districts is part of the town levy and the oversight of the district is via the town board.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Public benefit corporations in New York operate like quasi-private corporations, generally with boards appointed by elected officials.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They are a form of government bureaucracy in one sense but, unlike government agencies, public benefit corporations are exempt from some regulations.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Of particular importance, they can take out their own debt, allowing them to bypass legal limits on state debt.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] This allows them to make potentially risky capital and infrastructure investments without putting so much of the credit of New York on the line.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] However, it also allows them to avoid many of the oversight and reporting regulations that apply to state government.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Public benefit corporations get charters from New York and are usually designed to perform a specific, narrow function in the public interest.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The Metropolitan Transportation Authority manages public transportation in the New York Metropolitan Area (this includes the New York subway and public bus systems, as well as Metro-North Railroad and the Long Island Rail Road, and the Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority).
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] The New York State Thruway Authority originally only maintained the New York State Thruway from New York City to the Pennsylvania border southwest of Buffalo, but now maintains the toll-free Interstate 287 corridor.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] At the end of 2005, there were 866 public benefit corporations, of which 266 were public authorities.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Library districts are usually coextensive with the same school district but raise taxes separately and serve all the residents of the library district.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] They often form cooperative associations with other library districts for shared services, purchasing and cross-library lending.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Lake Protection and Rehabilitation districts are created to allow local government entities raise additional tax funding for projects in and around lakes.
[src:adirondack-mountains/administrative-divisions-of-new-york-state] Other special districts may include emergency rescue squads (also known as Consolidated Health Districts), sanitation, police, water, sewer, park, and parking.
